5. Pergamum. This city, the site of which still retains the name os Pergamo or Bergamah, situated in Mysia near the junction of two other streams with the Caicus, became very important from the time of Lysimachus under its own princes ; whose kingdom, bequeathed to Rome, formed the original province of Asia. It still remained a famous city, being esti- mated to consist of 40,000 citizens and 120,0oo inhabitants, able to vie with Smyrna and Ephesus, and, in the judgment of Pliny (N.
